Film Studies -- t16. Six Memos for the New Millennium : A Dialogue with Andreas Fickers on Epistemic Virtues in the Digital Humanities0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aFeaturing 28 leading international media scholars, Technics rethinks technology for the contemporary digital era, with cutting-edge theoretical, historiographical, and methodological interventions. The volume's contributors explore the ideas of Walter Benjamin, Ursula Le Guin, Bernhard Siegert, Gilbert Simondon, and Sylvia Wynter in conjunction with urgent questions concerning algorithmic media, digital infrastructures, generative AI, and geoengineering. An expansive collection of writings on media technologies in the digital age, Technics is an essential resource for students and scholars of film and media studies, digital humanities, science and technology studies, and the philosophy of technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aFilm and media studies, philosophy of technology, media theory, science and technology studies, media archaeology, digital humanities.1 aAlexander, Neta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaer, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaer, Nicholas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrock, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChateau, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenson, Shane, econtribut